To select all elements with the attribute "data-featured" set to true using the Zepto JavaScript library, follow these steps:

1. Include the Zepto library:
   Before using Zepto in your project, you need to include it. Add the following code to the head section of your HTML file:
   ```javascript
   <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/zepto/1.2.0/zepto.min.js"></script>
   ```

2. Use attribute selector:
   Zepto provides a powerful mechanism for working with selectors. To select all elements with the attribute "data-featured" set to true, you can use the '[data-featured="true"]' selector. Here's an example:
   ```javascript
   var featuredElements = $('[data-featured="true"]');
   ```

   The above code selects all HTML elements that have the "data-featured" attribute set to "true". If you want to encapsulate this functionality in a reusable function, you can define a function like this:
   ```javascript
   function getFeaturedElements() {
       return $('[data-featured="true"]');
   }
   ```

   When you call the `getFeaturedElements()` function, it will return all the featured elements.

Here's a complete example:

```javascript
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>ZepTo Example</title>
    <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/zepto/1.2.0/zepto.min.js"></script>
    <script>
        $(function(){
            function getFeaturedElements() {
                return $('[data-featured="true"]');
            }

            var featuredElements = getFeaturedElements();
            featuredElements.each(function(index, element){
                console.log(element);
            });

        });
    </script>
</head>
<body>
    <div data-featured="true">Div 1</div>
    <div data-featured="false">Div 2</div>
    <div data-featured="true">Div 3</div>
</body>
</html>
```

In the console, it will print out "Div 1" and "Div 3", which are the elements with the "data-featured" attribute set to "true".

